Post-Incident Analysis – README
📌 Overview

This project focuses on Post-Incident Analysis of a simulated phishing attack. The objective is to identify the root cause, document contributing factors, and calculate key SOC performance metrics such as MTTD (Mean Time to Detect) and MTTR (Mean Time to Respond).

🎯 Objective
Perform Root Cause Analysis (RCA) using the 5 Whys method
Identify contributing factors using a Fishbone Diagram
Calculate SOC metrics (MTTD, MTTR)
Document lessons learned and improvements
🧰 Tools Used
Google Sheets (RCA & metrics documentation)
Draw.io (Fishbone Diagram)
🔍 Root Cause Analysis (5 Whys)
Question	Answer
Why was email opened?	User clicked malicious link
Why was link clicked?	Weak email filtering
Why weak filtering?	No advanced spam protection
Why no protection?	Lack of security controls
Why lack of controls?	Poor security policy
🐟 Fishbone Diagram (Cause Analysis)

The Fishbone Diagram identifies key contributing factors:

People: Lack of user awareness
Process: No phishing response policy
Technology: Weak email filtering system
Management: Poor security governance

👉 Diagram created using Draw.io to visually represent causes of the incident.

📊 Metrics Calculation
Metric	Value
MTTD	2 hours
MTTR	4 hours
🧠 Metrics Summary (50 Words)

The analysis shows that the Mean Time to Detect (MTTD) was 2 hours, while the Mean Time to Respond (MTTR) was 4 hours. These metrics indicate moderate SOC efficiency. Improving monitoring systems and automating response processes can significantly reduce detection and response times in future incidents.

📚 Lessons Learned
Improve email filtering mechanisms
Conduct regular security awareness training
Implement stronger incident response policies
Enhance monitoring and alerting systems
✅ Conclusion

The post-incident analysis highlights gaps in user awareness, email security, and response processes. By addressing these issues and improving SOC capabilities, the organization can reduce risk exposure and improve incident response efficiency.
